1. Deorum, &c. Tacitus is at variance with Caesar, who says (f). 21, 5‘ ‘Deorum numero eos solos ducunt quos cernunt, et quorum aperte opibus iuvantur, solem et Vulcanum et Lunam ; reliquos ne sama quidem acceperunt.' Granting that the worship of Sun, Moon, and Fire, existed at that date, Caesar cannot but have been misin- formed in supposing that there was no other or higher worship (see SS. SS2.). We should suppose that Tacitus here selects for mention those most generally worshipped3 the cults spoken of else- waere (0· 39, 2; 40, 2; 43, 43 45, 3) being described as those of particular tribes or groups of tribes.
